<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-665-300  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 665 300.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 23 1990 v24 n30 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Database keeps earth's inventory. (Nature Conservancy's Biologicaland Conservation Data System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Nature Conservancy uses a database powered by Hewlett-Packard3000 minicomputers running Revelation Technologies' AdvancedRevelation DBMS to prioritize its conservation-oriented landpurchases.andP;  The Conservancy's Biological and Conservation DataSystem is distributed across 75 locations in the US, Canada, theCaribbean and Latin America.andP;  It consists of 45 integrated filessub-divided into 2,000 data fields.andP;  The data base holdsinformation pertaining to 65,000 plant and animal species in400,000 locations.andP;  This automated system enables the Conservancyto prioritize land acquisitions and manage a $100 million annualbudget.andP;  Current planning at the Conservancy call for a migrationto a local-area network system based on Banyan and AST Researchservers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   HP 3000 (Minicomputer) (usage)Advanced Revelation (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     Data base management systemsInformation resources managementInformation Storage and RetrievalNature conservationNature ConservancyMinicomputersStrategic Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>